column2: <ref group="note">The original version of the Artistic License is defined as non-free because it is overly vague  not because of the substance of the license. The FSF encourages projects to use the Clarified Artistic License instead.</ref>

column3: <ref name="fsf"></ref><ref></ref><ref></ref><ref>Are GPLv2 and CDDL incompatible? on hansenpartnership.com by James E.J. Bottomley "What the above analysis shows is that even though we presumed combination of GPLv2 and CDDL works to be a technical violation  there's no way actually to prosecute such a violation because we can’t develop a convincing theory of harm resulting. Because this makes it impossible to take the case to court  effectively it must be concluded that the combination of GPLv2 and CDDL  provided you’re following a GPLv2 compliance regime for all the code  is allowable." (23 February 2016)</ref><ref></ref><ref>GPL Violations Related to Combining ZFS and Linux on sfconservancy.org by Bradley M. Kuhn and Karen M. Sandler (February 25  2016)</ref>
<ref name="agplsection13"/><ref name="gplfsf">https://www.gnu.org/licenses/: "We use only licenses that are compatible with the GNU GPL for GNU software."</ref>
<ref group="note">But can be made compatible by upgrading to GPLv3 via the optional "or later" clause added in most GPLv2 license texts.</ref><ref name="gpl2gpl3comp"/>
<ref group="note">But not with GPLv2 without "or later" clause.</ref><ref name="gpl2gpl3comp"></ref>
<ref group="note">MPL 2.0 is GPL compatible unless marked "Incompatible with Secondary Licenses".</ref><ref></ref>
